**Full Research Context (Completed and Web-Grounded):**
Unencrypted credential transmission sends auth info (usernames/passwords) in plain text over networks (e.g., HTTP), vulnerable to interception (MitM, sniffing). Core concepts: plain-text, credentials, interception, pen testing. Risks: credential theft leading to account takeover.
**Industry Standards:** NIST SP 800-63B (requires TLS 1.2+ for credential service providers); OWASP Top 10 A07:2021 Identification/Authentication Failures (insecure transport); OWASP ASVS V2 (TLS enforcement, no plain-text auth); CISA Best Practices (completed): 'Use HTTPS Everywhere' - Enforce TLS for all auth traffic; redirect HTTP to HTTPS; implement HSTS; avoid HTTP in internal networks (CISA Alert AA20-133A, Secure Config for Cloud). PCI-DSS 4.0 Req 4: Encrypt transmission over public nets.
**Pen Testing Techniques:** 1. Recon: Check site for HTTP forms (Burp Spider). 2. Intercept: Burp Proxy/Wireshark (filter: http.request.method=="POST" &amp;&amp; frame contains "pass"). 3. Analyze: Look for base64/plain creds. Example: POST /login HTTP/1.1 ... user=admin&amp;password=secret. 4. Report: CVSS score ~7.5 (High).
**Remediation:** Mandate HTTPS, TLS 1.3, perfect forward secrecy; tools: sslscan, testssl.sh.
